## 1.10. Arrays

An array is a data structure that stores a fixed-size sequence of elements of the same type. Arrays are used to store collections of data that are accessed and manipulated using an index.

Here is an example of how to declare and initialize an array in Java:

```
int[] arr = new int[5];
```

This declares an array named `arr` that can store 5 integers. The `new` keyword is used to create the array and allocate memory for it.

You can also initialize an array using an array literal, which is a comma-separated list of values enclosed in curly braces:

```
int[] arr = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
```

This declares and initializes an array named `arr` with the values 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5.

To access an element in an array, you can use its index, which is a zero-based integer that specifies the position of the element in the array. For example:

```
int x = arr[0]; // x will be 1
int y = arr[4]; // y will be 5
```

You can also modify the elements of an array by assigning a new value to an index:

```
arr[0] = 10; // the first element of the array is now 10
arr[4] = 20; // the last element of the array is now 20
```

It is important to note that attempting to access an index that is out of bounds (i.e., less than 0 or greater than or equal to the size of the array) will result in an `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` being thrown.

