 package com.example;

 import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
 import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;

 @SpringBootApplication
 public class DemoApplication {

 public static void main(String[] args) {
 SpringApplication.run(DemoApplication.class, args);
 }
 }

Listing 2-2The DemoApplication.java File

The @SpringBootApplication annotation is a convenience annotation that adds all of the following:

@Configuration: Tells Spring that this class can be used by the Spring container as a source of bean definitions.

@EnableAutoConfiguration: Tells Spring Boot to start adding beans based on the classpath and the contents of this annotation. For example, if spring-webmvc is on the classpath, this annotation will automatically enable Spring MVC.

@ComponentScan: Tells Spring to look for other components, configurations, and services in the package, allowing it to find the DemoController.java file.

The DemoApplication.java file is the entry point for the application. When you run the application, Spring Boot will start up an embedded Tomcat server and deploy the application.

### Creating the DemoController.java File

The DemoController.java file is the controller for the application. It will handle HTTP requests and return HTTP responses.

Create a new file named DemoController.java in the com.example package and add the code from Listing 2-3.

Listing 2-3The DemoController.java File

package com.example;

import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;

@RestController
public class DemoController {
 @GetMapping("/")
 public String index() {
 return "Hello, World!";
 }
}

Listing 2-4The DemoController.java File

The @RestController annotation is a convenience annotation that combines @Controller and @ResponseBody. It tells Spring that this class can be used by the Spring container as a source of controllers and that the methods should return the data directly instead of rendering a view.

The @GetMapping annotation is a convenience annotation that combines @RequestMapping(method = RequestMethod.GET) and @ResponseBody. It tells Spring that this method should handle HTTP GET requests and return the data directly instead of rendering a view.

The index() method is the method that will handle HTTP GET requests to the root URL ("/") of the application. It returns the string "Hello, World!".

### Running the Application

To run the application, open a terminal window and navigate to the project directory. Then run the following command:

./mvnw spring-boot:run

This will start the application and deploy it to an embedded Tomcat server. You can then open a web browser and navigate to http://localhost:8080/ to see the "Hello, World!" message.

