# 3. Thymeleaf

Chan Hin Lik ^{ }
(1)
Hong Kong, Kowloon, Hong Kong

Thymeleaf is a modern server-side Java template engine for both web and standalone environments. It is designed to be easy to use and to integrate with Spring Boot. In this chapter, you will learn how to use Thymeleaf to create HTML templates for your application.

## Creating the Thymeleaf Template

To create a Thymeleaf template, create a new file named index.html in the src/main/resources/templates directory and add the code from Listing 3-1.

Listing 3-1The index.html File

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html xmlns:th="http://www.thymeleaf.org">
<head>
 <title>Spring Boot Thymeleaf Example</title>
</head>
<body>
 <h1 th:text="${message}">Hello, World!</h1>
</body>
</html>

Listing 3-2The index.html File

The index.html file is a Thymeleaf template that contains the HTML markup for the home page of the application. It uses the th:text attribute to bind the message variable to the text content of the h1 element. If the message variable is not set, it will default to "Hello, World!".

## Creating the DemoController.java File

To use the Thymeleaf template in the application, you need to modify the DemoController.java file to return the template instead of a string.

Modify the DemoController.java file to match the code in Listing 3-2.

Listing 3-2The DemoController.java File

package com.example;

import org.springframework.stereotype.Controller;
import org.springframework.ui.Model;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;

@Controller
public class DemoController {
 @GetMapping("/")
 public String index(Model model) {
 model.addAttribute("message", "Hello, Thymeleaf!");
 return "index";
 }
}

Listing 3-3The DemoController.java File

The @Controller annotation is a convenience annotation that combines @Component and @ResponseBody. It tells Spring that this class can be used by the Spring container as a source of controllers.

The index() method is the method that will handle HTTP GET requests to the root URL ("/") of the application. It adds the message variable to the model and returns the name of the template, "index".

## Running the Application

To run the application, open a terminal window and navigate to the project directory. Then run the following command:

./mvnw spring-boot:run

This will start the application and deploy it to an embedded Tomcat server. You can then open a web browser and navigate to http://localhost:8080/ to see the "Hello, Thymeleaf!" message.

## Summary

In this chapter, you learned how to use Thymeleaf to create HTML templates for your application. You also learned how to bind variables to the template using the th:text attribute.

